 Collections\n* Concertzender Gregoriaans Radio \u2013 [http://streams.greenhost.nl:8080/gregoriaans.m3u live stream]\n* [http://www.gregor-und-taube.de/index.html] Website of Anton Stingl jun. including articles and editions of Sankt Gallen notations\n* [https://verbumchanting.wixsite.com/main \"The living textbook\" on the choral notation of the Gregorian chant]\n\n{{Chant}}\n{{Navboxes\n|list=\n{{Medieval music}}\n{{Mass}}\n{{History of the Catholic Church}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2011}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gregorian Chant}}\n[[Category:Catholic music]]\n[[Category:Christian chants]]\n[[Category:Order of Mass]]\n[[Category:Tridentine Mass]]\n[[Category:Western plainchant]]\n[[Category:Pope Gregory I]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "Journal cites:, templated 3 journal cites", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gregorian_chant"}
{"title_page": "Mareth Line", "text_new": "{{short description|System of fortifications defending Tunisia during WW2}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox military installation\n| name = Mareth Line\n| ensign =\n| native_name =\n| partof = French defence of Tunisia\n| location =\n| nearest_town = <!-- used in military test site infobox -->\n| country = Tunisia\n| image = File:MarethMap1943 en.png\n|image_size = 250px\n| alt =\n| caption = Mareth Line in 1943\n|coordinates = {{coord|33|38|00|N|10|18|00|E|display=inline,title}}\n| ownership = French colonial administration of Tunisia\n| operator = French army (1939\u20131940)\n| controlledby = [[Panzer Army Africa|German\u2013Italian Panzer Army]] ({{lang|de|Deutsch-Italienische Panzerarmee}}/{{lang|it|Armata Corazzata Italo-Tedesca}}) [1943]\n| built = {{start date|1936}}\n| used =  {{end date|March 1943}}\n| builder = {{lang|fr|Le Deuxi\u00e8me Bureau au Travail}}\n| materials = reinforced concrete\n| height = {{convert|2200|ft|m}}\n| length = {{convert|25|mi|km}}\n| fate = Lapsed into desuetude after 1943\n| condition = Derelict\n| battles = Battle of the Mareth Line\n| events =\n| past_commanders = [[Erwin Rommel]]\n| garrison = 1943, east to west: [[136th Infantry Division Giovani Fascisti|136th Infantry Division ''Giovani Fascisti'']], [[101st Motorised Division Trieste|101st Motorised Division ''Trieste'']], [[90th Light Infantry Division (Wehrmacht)|90th Light Division]], [[80th Infantry Division La Spezia (Airlanding)|80th Infantry Division ''La Spezia'']], [[16th Motorised Division Pistoia|16th Motorised Division ''Pistoia'']], [[164th Infantry Division (Wehrmacht)|164th Light ''Afrika'' Division]] [[15th Panzer Division (Wehrmacht)|15th Panzer Division]] (32 operational tanks)<br /> Reserve: [[21st Panzer Division (Wehrmacht)|21st Panzer Division]], [[10th Panzer Division (Wehrmacht)|10th Panzer Division]] (110 operational tanks)\n| footnotes = Djebel Tebaga\u2013Djebel Melab: {{lang|it|Raggruppamento Sahariano}}\n}}\nThe '''Mareth Line''' was a system of fortifications built by France in southern [[Tunisia]] in the late 1930s. to defend Tunisia against attacks from the [[Kingdom of Italy#Fascist regime (1922\u20131943)|Italian]] colony of [[Libya]]. The line occupied a point where the routes into Tunisia from the south converged, leading toward Mareth, with the [[Mediterranean Sea]] to the east and a sand sea on the other.\n\nThe line ran north of Wadi Zigzaou for about {{cvt|50|km|mi|abbr=on}} south-westwards from the [[Gulf of Gab\u00e8s]] to Cheguimi and the Djebel (mountain) Matmata on the Dahar plateau between the [[Grand Erg Oriental|Great Eastern Sand Sea]] and the [[Matmata, Tunisia|Matmata]] hills. The [[Tebaga Gap]], between the Mareth line and the Great Eastern Sand Sea, a potential route by which an invader could outflank the Mareth line, was not given consideration until 1938.\n\nTunisia was occupied by [[Axis powers|Axis]] forces after [[Operation Torch]] in 1942 and the line was used by the Axis to defend against the British and Allied [[Eighth Army (United Kingdom)|Eighth Army]], which had conquered Libya early in 1943.\n\n==Background==\n\n===French strategy===\nIn 1930s the defence of the [[French colonial empire]] (French Indochina, Pacific Islands, West Indies, African colonies and Syria\u2013Lebanon) was left to the [[French Foreign Legion]], colonial and \"native\" units, the {{lang|fr|[[Marine nationale]]}} (Navy) and the {{lang|fr|[[Arm\u00e9e de l'Air]]}} (Air Force). By the late 1930s, the Navy had only one aircraft carrier and the {{lang|fr|Arm\u00e9e de l'Air}} could spare only second-rate aircraft. [[French Algeria|Algeria]], [[French Protectorate in Morocco|Morocco]] and Tunisia provided much of the manpower of the {{lang|fr|[[Troupes coloniales|Arm\u00e9e coloniale]]}} and Tunisia, with the Italian colony of [[Italian Libya|Libya]] to the east, was excepted from the priority given to the defence of metropolitan France.{{sfnm|1a1=Kaufmann|1a2=Kaufmann|1y=2006|1p=89|2a1=Jackson|2y=2000|2pp=332\u2013333}}\n\nFrench plans for defence of Tunisia assumed that Italy would launch an overwhelming assault that France could not easily oppose. Italy was expected to launch attacks on [[Egypt]] and Tunisia as soon as war was declared, with the Italian Navy securing supply and blocking any substantial Anglo-French relief. With a force of six divisions, a fortress division and a cavalry division to defend Tunisia, the French army considered the construction of a \"[[Maginot Line]] in the desert\" ({{lang|fr|ligne Maginot du d\u00e9sert}}).{{sfn|Playfair|1954|p=92}}\n\n===Geography===\n\nThe geography of central Tunisia is dominated by the [[Atlas Mountains]], while the northern and southern portions are largely flat. The primary feature in the south is the Matmata Hills, a range running north-south roughly parallel to the Mediterranean coast. West of the hills, the land is the inhospitable [[Jebel Dahar]] then the Dehar region of desert to the west, making the region between the hills and the coast the only easily traversed approach to northern Tunisia.{{sfn|Ford|2012|p=46}} A smaller line of hills runs east\u2013west along the northern edge of the Matmata range, further complicating this approach. At the far northern end of the Matmata Hills is the [[Tebaga Gap]].\n\n===Plans===\n\n[[File:Tunisia Topography.png|thumb|upright=.75|{{center|Topographic map of Tunisia}}]]\nIn January 1934 planning began on the new fortifications; Infantry officers selected the sites for strongpoints to dominate the ground in front with overlapping fields of fire. In 1936, the French government provided funds for construction after Italy formed the [[Axis powers|Rome\u2013Berlin Axis]] with Germany, creating a greater threat to French security in North Africa.{{sfn|Kaufmann|Kaufmann|2006|p=90}}{{efn|The cost of the Mareth Line and its forward defences was similar to that of {{lang|fr|ouvrage of St Agnes}} in the Alps.{{sfn|Kaufmann|Kaufmann|2006|p=90}}}} The casemates designed for the line had much less concrete than comparable examples in France and had no {{lang|fr|[[wkt:fosse|foss\u00e9]]}} (gap) rather a stable door, in case the lower part was blocked by d\u00e9bris. In September 1936, during a meeting with General [[Alphonse Joseph Georges|Joseph Georges]], it was agreed that the fortification of the Mareth Line, Bizerte, Medenine, Ben Gardane and Foum Tathouine must be completed.{{sfn|Kaufmann|Kaufmann|2006|p=90}}\n\nMedenine, Ben Gardane to the west and Foum Tathouine to the east, were south of the proposed line, Foum Tathouine being the place where the routes to Mareth passed through the bottleneck between the Matmata Mountains and the sea. The line was divided into eastern and western sectors with a main line of resistance and a reserve line about {{cvt|1.5|km|mi|order=flip|abbr=on}} back. A {{lang|fr|secteur d\u00e9fensif}} (SD) was to be built on the rocky Dahar Plateau, which later became part of an SD across the Matmata Hills to [[Kebili]] on the edge of the [[Chott el Djerid]]. The chott and Chott El Fedjaj drained across Tunisia into Wadi Akarit, across Tunisia but Wadi Akarit was only sketchily fortified, the French concentrating on the Mareth Line {{cvt|50|km|mi|order=flip|abbr=on}} south, to cover Gabes.{{sfn|Kaufmann|Kaufmann|2006|p=90}} The gap between the Mareth Line and the Great Eastern Sand Sea, a potential route by which an invader could outflank the Mareth line, was not given consideration until 1938. General [[Georges Catroux]] and Colonel Gautsch surveyed the area and in their assessment predicted that three divisions could advance from the Libyan border to Ksar (fortified village) el Hallouf and Bir (well) Soltane in six days and then advance into the gaps either side of Djebel Melab and those between Djebel Tebaga and the Matmata Hills. {{sfnm|1a1=Kaufmann|1a2=Kaufmann|1y=2006|1p=89|2a1=Playfair|2y=2004|2p=333}}\n\n==The Mareth Line==\n\n[[File:Mareth Line Panel.jpg|thumb|{{centre|Mareth Line Panel}}]]\nThe Mareth Line consisted of casemates surrounded by barbed wire and built for all-round defence in the main and reserve lines, the obstacles being doubled on the fronts and sides. The strongpoints in the main line included flanking machine-gun casemates and anti-tank gun positions; in the reserve line artillery emplacements provided covering fire in the gaps between the strongpoints in the main line. Some of the flanking casemates for machine-guns covering the gaps were connected by galleries; strongpoints on the plain and in hills had anti-tank positions. An anti-tank obstacle of vertical rails was built along the front of the line and the sides of Wadi Zigzaou were steepened. Eight artillery casemates, forty infantry casemates or blockhouses and fifteen command posts were built. The eastern sector had twelve strongpoints in the main line and eleven in the reserve line. The western sector had eleven strongpoints in the main line and seven in the reserve line.{{sfn|Kaufmann|Kaufmann|2006|p=90}}\n\nIn the Matmata hills, Ksar el Hallouf covered an anti-tank ditch which continued the position beyond the main line which ended on the foothills. An infantry position was dug into the Matmata hills at Ksar-el-Hallouf and in the Dahar beyond, a strongpoint at Bir Soltane had two 75 mm turrets, removed from [[Char 2C]] tanks built in 1918. At Ben Gardane an advanced position was built consisting of a square redoubt inside an anti-tank ditch with casemates on the flanks and concrete infantry shelters. Small triangular strongpoints at the corners were surrounded by anti-tank rail obstacles that continued around the position. The Mareth line was equipped with obsolescent 47 mm naval guns for anti-tank defence and some new [[25 mm Hotchkiss anti-tank gun|25 mm anti-tank guns]] and infantry small-arms. The artillery casemates with 75 mm guns and most of the blockhouses and casemates had embrasures for automatic weapons. In 1938 work the Mareth line was so important that work on coast defences was stopped and in 1939 the line was occupied by colonial divisions and some locally-raised units. After the outbreak of the war, a line of advanced positions ({{lang|fr|avant-postes}}) was built on high ground at Aram {{cvt|10|km|mi|order=flip|abbr=on}} south of the main line.{{sfn|Kaufmann|Kaufmann|2006|p=90}}\n\n==Second World War==\n\n===Demilitarisation and Axis occupation===\n\n{{main|Battle of Medenine}}\n\nThe [[Second World War]] began in 1939 but the Mareth Line saw no use from 1939\u20131940, as Italy remained neutral until a few days before the [[Armistice of 22 June 1940]], after which, the line was demilitarised by an Italo-German commission. In November 1942, the British [[Eighth Army (United Kingdom)|Eighth Army]] ([[General (United Kingdom)|General]] [[Bernard Montgomery]]) defeated {{lang|de|[[Panzer Army Africa|Panzerarmee Afrika]]}} at the [[Second Battle of El Alamein]] and the British [[First Army (United Kingdom)|First Army]] landed in French North Africa in [[Operation Torch]]. Axis forces occupied Tunisia in the [[Tunisia Campaign]] and from November 1942 to March 1943, the {{lang|de|Panzerarmee}} conducted a fighting retreat through Egypt and Libya, pursued by the Eighth Army. Axis engineers refurbished the Mareth Line for occupation by the {{lang|de|Panzerarmee}} and by March 1943, more than {{convert|100|km|mi|order=flip}} of [[barbed wire]], 100,000 anti-tank mines and 70,000 anti-personnel mines had been laid, bunkers had been reinforced with concrete and armed with anti-tank and anti-aircraft guns.  In March 1943, the Eighth Army reached the Libya\u2013Tunisia border and paused at Medenine to prepare to attack the Mareth Line.{{sfn|Playfair|2004|p=324}}\n\nAxis forces were renamed the [[First Army (Italy)|Italian 1st Army]] (General [[Giovanni Messe]]) and attempted a spoiling attack, {{lang|de|[[Operation Capri|Unternehmen Capri]]}} (Operation Capri, the Battle of Medenine). The attack failed and the Axis troops withdrew to the Mareth Line, to await the British attack.{{sfn|Playfair|2004|p=324}} The Mareth Line was garrisoned by the [[136th Infantry Division Giovani Fascisti|136th Infantry Division \"Giovani Fascisti\"]], [[101st Motorised Division Trieste|101st Motorised Division \"Trieste\"]], [[90th Light Infantry Division (Wehrmacht)|90th Light Division]], [[80th Infantry Division La Spezia (Airlanding)|80th Infantry Division \"La Spezia\"]], [[16th Motorised Division Pistoia|16th Motorised Division \"Pistoia\"]], [[164th Infantry Division (Wehrmacht)|164th Light ''Afrika'' Division]] and the [[15th Panzer Division (Wehrmacht)|15th Panzer Division]] with 32 operational tanks. In reserve were the [[21st Panzer Division (Wehrmacht)|21st Panzer Division]] and the [[10th Panzer Division (Wehrmacht)|10th Panzer Division]] with 110 operational tanks. The line from Djebel Tebaga\u2013Djebel Melab was held by the {{lang|it|Raggruppamento Sahariano}}.{{sfn|Playfair|2004|p=333}} The British survey of the Mareth Line, the positions of [[Zarat, Tunisia|Zarat]] sudest (Zaret South-West), Ouerzi, Ouerzi Ouest (Ouerzi West), Ouerzi Est (Ouerzi East), Ksiba Ouest and Ksiba Est being of particular interest, was assisted by General Marcel Rime-Bruneau, a former Chief of Staff of the Tunisian garrison and Captain Paul Mezan, the former Garrison Engineer of the Mareth Line.{{sfn|Playfair|2004|p=332}}\n\n===Battle of the Mareth Line===\n{{Main article|Battle of the Mareth Line}}\n\n[[File:Mareth line object.jpg|thumb|{{center|Infantry bunker of the Mareth Line}}]]\nOn 19 March 1943, the Eighth Army made a frontal assault against the Mareth Line in Operation Pugilist. The [[50th (Northumbrian) Infantry Division|50th Northumbrian Infantry Division]] penetrated the Line near [[Zarat, Tunisia|Zarat]] but was driven back by the [[33rd Infantry Division (Wehrmacht)|15th Panzer Division]] and the{{lang|it|Giovani Fascisti}} on 22 March.<ref>[https://adviceandresearch.blogspot.com/2019/06/division-giovani-fascisti-in-1943.html Giovani Fascisti division at Mareth]</ref> Earlier reconnaissance by the [[Long Range Desert Group]] had shown that the Line could be outflanked. A force could pass through the southern Matmata Hills, reach the Tebaga Gap from the west and pass on to the coastal plain behind the Mareth Line. At the same time as Pugilist, Montgomery had sent the [[2nd New Zealand Division]] around the Matmata Hills but its attack was contained at the Tebaga Gap from 21 to 24 March. Montgomery sent the [[1st (United Kingdom) Division|1st Armoured Division]] ([[X Corps (United Kingdom)|X Corps]]) to reinforce the attack at the Tebaga Gap. The British attacked again in [[Battle of the Mareth Line#Operation Supercharge II|Operation Supercharge II]] on 26 March and broke through the gap the next day. This success, combined with a fresh frontal assault, made the Mareth Line untenable but the Italian 1st Army escaped encirclement when the 1st Armoured Division was held up at El Hamma and the Axis forces retreated to [[Wadi Akarit]], {{convert|60|km|mi|order=flip}} to the north.\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{reflist|20em}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |title=The Oxford Companion to World War II |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford |year=2001 |editor-first=I. C. B. |editor-last=Dear |isbn=0-19-860446-7}}\n* {{cite book |ref={{harvid|Ford|2012}}\n|last=Ford |first=K. |others=Steve Noon |title=The Mareth Line 1943: The End in Africa |year=2012 |publisher=Osprey |location=Oxford |edition=ebook |isbn=978-1-78096-094-4}}\n* {{cite book |last=Jackson |first=P. |title=France and the Nazi Menace: Intelligence and Policy Making, 1933\u20131939 |year=2000 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford |isbn=0-19820-834-0 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |ref={{harvid|Kaufmann|Kaufmann|2006}}\n|last1=Kaufmann |first1=J. E. |last2=Kaufmann |first2=H. W. |title=Fortress France: The Maginot Line and French Defenses in World War II |year=2006 |publisher=Praeger Security International (Greenwood Publishing) |location=Westport, CT |edition=online scan |isbn=0-275-98345-5}}\n* {{cite book |ref={{harvid|Playfair|1954}}\n|first1= I. S. O. |last1=Playfair |author1-link=Ian Stanley Ord Playfair |first2=G. M. S. |last2=Stitt |first3= C. J. C. |last3=Molony |first4= S. E. |last4=Toomer |editor-last=Butler |editor-first=J. R. M. |editor-link=James Ramsay Montagu Butler |series=History of the Second World War, United Kingdom Military Series |title=The Mediterranean and Middle East: The Early Successes Against Italy (to May 1941) |volume=I |publisher=[[HMSO]] |edition=4th impr.|year=1954 |isbn=1-84574-065-3 |display-authors=1}}\n* {{cite book |ref={{harvid|Playfair|2004}}\n|first1= I. S. O. |last1=Playfair |first2= C. J. C. |last2=and Molony |first3= F. C. |last3=Flynn |first4= T. P. |last4=Gleave |editor-last=Butler |editor-first=J. R. M. |title=The Mediterranean and Middle East: The Destruction of the Axis Forces in Africa |volume=IV |series=History of the Second World War United Kingdom Military Series |orig-year=1966 |year=2004 |publisher=HMSO |location=London |edition=pbk. facs repr. Naval & Military Press, Uckfield |isbn=1-84574-068-8 |display-authors=1}}\n* {{cite book |last=Prior-Palmer |first=Brigadier G. E. |url=http://www.warlinks.com/armour/8th_armoured/chapter_2.html |accessdate=3 June 2015 |title=A Short History of the 8th Armoured Brigade |chapter=II, Medenine to Tunis |date=March 1946 |publisher=H.Q. 8th Armoured Brigade |location=Hanover |others=no isbn}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book |last=Gauch\u00e9 |first=Maurice |series=Archives d'histoire contemporaine |title=Le Deuxi\u00e8me Bureau au Travail, 1935\u20131940 |trans-title=The [[Deuxi\u00e8me Bureau]] at Work |language=French |year=1953 |publisher=Amiot Dumont |location=Paris |oclc=3093195}}\n* {{cite book |last=Stevens |first=Major-General W. G. |series=The Official History of New Zealand in the Second World War 1939\u20131945 |title=Bardia to Enfidaville |chapter=8\u201310 |url=http://www.nzetc.org/tm/scholarly/tei-WH2Bard-c8-1.html |location=Wellington, NZ |publisher=Historical Publications Branch |year=1962 |oclc=4377202}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Mareth Line}}\n* [http://cgsc.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/singleitem/collection/p4013coll8/id/4161/rec/1 Strader, J. W. Tactical Bomber Operations in the ETO (1944)]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110710212242/http://www.exploguide.com/site/mareth-line-military-museum-mareth Travel tips to visit the Mareth Line museum]\n\n{{World War II}}\n\n[[Category:Tunisian Campaign]]\n[[Category:World War II defensive lines]]\n[[Category:World War II sites in Tunisia]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|System of fortifications defending Tunisia during WW2}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox military installation\n| name = Mareth Line\n| ensign =\n| native_name =\n| partof = French defence of Tunisia\n| location =\n| nearest_town = <!-- used in military test site infobox -->\n| country = Tunisia\n| image = File:MarethMap1943 en.png\n|image_size = 250px\n| alt =\n| caption = Mareth Line in 1943\n|coordinates = {{coord|33|38|00|N|10|18|00|E|display=inline,title}}\n| ownership = French colonial administration of Tunisia\n| operator = French army (1939\u20131940)\n| controlledby = [[Panzer Army Africa|German\u2013Italian Panzer Army]] ({{lang|de|Deutsch-Italienische Panzerarmee}}/{{lang|it|Armata Corazzata Italo-Tedesca}}) [1943]\n| built = {{start date|1936}}\n| used =  {{end date|March 1943}}\n| builder = {{lang|fr|Le Deuxi\u00e8me Bureau au Travail}}\n| materials = reinforced concrete\n| height = {{convert|2200|ft|m}}\n| length = {{convert|25|mi|km}}\n| fate = Lapsed into desuetude after 1943\n| condition = Derelict\n| battles = Battle of the Mareth Line\n| events =\n| past_commanders = [[Erwin Rommel]]\n| garrison = 1943, east to west: [[136th Infantry Division Giovani Fascisti|136th Infantry Division ''Giovani Fascisti'']], [[101st Motorised Division Trieste|101st Motorised Division ''Trieste'']], [[90th Light Infantry Division (Wehrmacht)|90th Light Division]], [[80th Infantry Division La Spezia (Airlanding)|80th Infantry Division ''La Spezia'']], [[16th Motorised Division Pistoia|16th Motorised Division ''Pistoia'']], [[164th Infantry Division (Wehrmacht)|164th Light ''Afrika'' Division]] [[15th Panzer Division (Wehrmacht)|15th Panzer Division]] (32 operational tanks)<br /> Reserve: [[21st Panzer Division (Wehrmacht)|21st Panzer Division]], [[10th Panzer Division (Wehrmacht)|10th Panzer Division]] (110 operational tanks)\n| footnotes = Djebel Tebaga\u2013Djebel Melab: {{lang|it|Raggruppamento Sahariano}}\n}}\nThe '''Mareth Line''' was a system of fortifications built by France in southern [[Tunisia]] in the late 1930s. to defend Tunisia against attacks from the [[Kingdom of Italy#Fascist regime (1922\u20131943)|Italian]] colony of [[Libya]]. The line occupied a point where the routes into Tunisia from the south converged, leading toward Mareth, with the [[Mediterranean Sea]] to the east and a sand sea on the other.\n\nThe line ran north of Wadi Zigzaou for about {{cvt|50|km|mi|abbr=on}} south-westwards from the [[Gulf of Gab\u00e8s]] to Cheguimi and the Djebel (mountain) Matmata on the Dahar plateau between the [[Grand Erg Oriental|Great Eastern Sand Sea]] and the [[Matmata, Tunisia|Matmata]] hills. The [[Tebaga Gap]], between the Mareth line and the Great Eastern Sand Sea, a potential route by which an invader could outflank the Mareth line, was not given consideration until 1938.\n\nTunisia was occupied by [[Axis powers|Axis]] forces after [[Operation Torch]] in 1942 and the line was used by the Axis to defend against the British and Allied [[Eighth Army (United Kingdom)|Eighth Army]], which had conquered Libya early in 1943.\n\n==Background==\n\n===French strategy===\nIn 1930s the defence of the [[French colonial empire]] (French Indochina, Pacific Islands, West Indies, African colonies and Syria\u2013Lebanon) was left to the [[French Foreign Legion]], colonial and \"native\" units, the {{lang|fr|[[Marine nationale]]}} (Navy) and the {{lang|fr|[[Arm\u00e9e de l'Air]]}} (Air Force). By the late 1930s, the Navy had only one aircraft carrier and the {{lang|fr|Arm\u00e9e de l'Air}} could spare only second-rate aircraft. [[French Algeria|Algeria]], [[French Protectorate in Morocco|Morocco]] and Tunisia provided much of the manpower of the {{lang|fr|[[Troupes coloniales|Arm\u00e9e coloniale]]}} and Tunisia, with the Italian colony of [[Italian Libya|Libya]] to the east, was excepted from the priority given to the defence of metropolitan France.{{sfnm|1a1=Kaufmann|1a2=Kaufmann|1y=2006|1p=89|2a1=Jackson|2y=2000|2pp=332\u2013333}}\n\nFrench plans for defence of Tunisia assumed that Italy would launch an overwhelming assault that France could not easily oppose. Italy was expected to launch attacks on [[Egypt]] and Tunisia as soon as war was declared, with the Italian Navy securing supply and blocking any substantial Anglo-French relief. With a force of six divisions, a fortress division and a cavalry division to defend Tunisia, the French army considered the construction of a \"[[Maginot Line]] in the desert\" ({{lang|fr|ligne Maginot du d\u00e9sert}}).{{sfn|Playfair|1954|p=92}}\n\n===Geography===\n\nThe geography of central Tunisia is dominated by the [[Atlas Mountains]], while the northern and southern portions are largely flat. The primary feature in the south is the Matmata Hills, a range running north-south roughly parallel to the Mediterranean coast. West of the hills, the land is the inhospitable [[Jebel Dahar]] then the Dehar region of desert to the west, making the region between the hills and the coast the only easily traversed approach to northern Tunisia.{{sfn|Ford|2012|p=46}} A smaller line of hills runs east\u2013west along the northern edge of the Matmata range, further complicating this approach. At the far northern end of the Matmata Hills is the [[Tebaga Gap]].\n\n===Plans===\n\n[[File:Tunisia Topography.png|thumb|upright=.75|{{center|Topographic map of Tunisia}}]]\nIn January 1934 planning began on the new fortifications; Infantry officers selected the sites for strongpoints to dominate the ground in front with overlapping fields of fire. In 1936, the French government provided funds for construction after Italy formed the [[Axis powers|Rome\u2013Berlin Axis]] with Germany, creating a greater threat to French security in North Africa.{{sfn|Kaufmann|Kaufmann|2006|p=90}}{{efn|The cost of the Mareth Line and its forward defences was similar to that of {{lang|fr|ouvrage of St Agnes}} in the Alps.{{sfn|Kaufmann|Kaufmann|2006|p=90}}}} The casemates designed for the line had much less concrete than comparable examples in France and had no {{lang|fr|[[wkt:fosse|foss\u00e9]]}} (gap) rather a stable door, in case the lower part was blocked by d\u00e9bris. In September 1936, during a meeting with General [[Alphonse Joseph Georges|Joseph Georges]], it was agreed that the fortification of the Mareth Line, Bizerte, Medenine, Ben Gardane and Foum Tathouine must be completed.{{sfn|Kaufmann|Kaufmann|2006|p=90}}\n\nMedenine, Ben Gardane to the west and Foum Tathouine to the east, were south of the proposed line, Foum Tathouine being the place where the routes to Mareth passed through the bottleneck between the Matmata Mountains and the sea. The line was divided into eastern and western sectors with a main line of resistance and a reserve line about {{cvt|1.5|km|mi|order=flip|abbr=on}} back. A {{lang|fr|secteur d\u00e9fensif}} (SD) was to be built on the rocky Dahar Plateau, which later became part of an SD across the Matmata Hills to [[Kebili]] on the edge of the [[Chott el Djerid]]. The chott and Chott El Fedjaj drained across Tunisia into Wadi Akarit, across Tunisia but Wadi Akarit was only sketchily fortified, the French concentrating on the Mareth Line {{cvt|50|km|mi|order=flip|abbr=on}} south, to cover Gabes.{{sfn|Kaufmann|Kaufmann|2006|p=90}} The gap between the Mareth Line and the Great Eastern Sand Sea, a potential route by which an invader could outflank the Mareth line, was not given consideration until 1938. General [[Georges Catroux]] and Colonel Gautsch surveyed the area and in their assessment predicted that three divisions could advance from the Libyan border to Ksar (fortified village) el Hallouf and Bir (well) Soltane in six days and then advance into the gaps either side of Djebel Melab and those between Djebel Tebaga and the Matmata Hills. {{sfnm|1a1=Kaufmann|1a2=Kaufmann|1y=2006|1p=89|2a1=Playfair|2y=2004|2p=333}}\n\n==The Mareth Line==\n\n[[File:Mareth Line Panel.jpg|thumb|{{centre|Mareth Line Panel}}]]\nThe Mareth Line consisted of casemates surrounded by barbed wire and built for all-round defence in the main and reserve lines, the obstacles being doubled on the fronts and sides. The strongpoints in the main line included flanking machine-gun casemates and anti-tank gun positions; in the reserve line artillery emplacements provided covering fire in the gaps between the strongpoints in the main line. Some of the flanking casemates for machine-guns covering the gaps were connected by galleries; strongpoints on the plain and in hills had anti-tank positions. An anti-tank obstacle of vertical rails was built along the front of the line and the sides of Wadi Zigzaou were steepened. Eight artillery casemates, forty infantry casemates or blockhouses and fifteen command posts were built. The eastern sector had twelve strongpoints in the main line and eleven in the reserve line. The western sector had eleven strongpoints in the main line and seven in the reserve line.{{sfn|Kaufmann|Kaufmann|2006|p=90}}\n\nIn the Matmata hills, Ksar el Hallouf covered an anti-tank ditch which continued the position beyond the main line which ended on the foothills. An infantry position was dug into the Matmata hills at Ksar-el-Hallouf and in the Dahar beyond, a strongpoint at Bir Soltane had two 75 mm turrets, removed from [[Char 2C]] tanks built in 1918. At Ben Gardane an advanced position was built consisting of a square redoubt inside an anti-tank ditch with casemates on the flanks and concrete infantry shelters. Small triangular strongpoints at the corners were surrounded by anti-tank rail obstacles that continued around the position. The Mareth line was equipped with obsolescent 47 mm naval guns for anti-tank defence and some new [[25 mm Hotchkiss anti-tank gun|25 mm anti-tank guns]] and infantry small-arms. The artillery casemates with 75 mm guns and most of the blockhouses and casemates had embrasures for automatic weapons. In 1938 work the Mareth line was so important that work on coast defences was stopped and in 1939 the line was occupied by colonial divisions and some locally-raised units. After the outbreak of the war, a line of advanced positions ({{lang|fr|avant-postes}}) was built on high ground at Aram {{cvt|10|km|mi|order=flip|abbr=on}} south of the main line.{{sfn|Kaufmann|Kaufmann|2006|p=90}}\n\n==Second World War==\n\n===Demilitarisation and Axis occupation===\n\n{{main|Battle of Medenine}}\n\nThe [[Second World War]] began in 1939 but the Mareth Line saw no use from 1939\u20131940, as Italy remained neutral until a few days before the [[Armistice of 22 June 1940]], after which, the line was demilitarised by an Italo-German commission. In November 1942, the British [[Eighth Army (United Kingdom)|Eighth Army]] ([[General (United Kingdom)|General]] [[Bernard Montgomery]]) defeated {{lang|de|[[Panzer Army Africa|Panzerarmee Afrika]]}} at the [[Second Battle of El Alamein]] and the British [[First Army (United Kingdom)|First Army]] landed in French North Africa in [[Operation Torch]]. Axis forces occupied Tunisia in the [[Tunisia Campaign]] and from November 1942 to March 1943, the {{lang|de|Panzerarmee}} conducted a fighting retreat through Egypt and Libya, pursued by the Eighth Army. Axis engineers refurbished the Mareth Line for occupation by the {{lang|de|Panzerarmee}} and by March 1943, more than {{convert|100|km|mi|order=flip}} of [[barbed wire]], 100,000 anti-tank mines and 70,000 anti-personnel mines had been laid, bunkers had been reinforced with concrete and armed with anti-tank and anti-aircraft guns.  In March 1943, the Eighth Army reached the Libya\u2013Tunisia border and paused at Medenine to prepare to attack the Mareth Line. Axis forces were renamed the [[First Army (Italy)|Italian 1st Army]] (General [[Giovanni Messe]]) and attempted a spoiling attack, {{lang|de|[[Operation Capri|Unternehmen Capri]]}} (Operation Capri, the Battle of Medenine). The attack failed and the Axis troops withdrew to the Mareth Line, to await the British attack.{{sfn|Playfair|2004|p=324}}\n\nThe Mareth Line was garrisoned by the [[136th Infantry Division Giovani Fascisti|136th Infantry Division \"Giovani Fascisti\"]], [[101st Motorised Division Trieste|101st Motorised Division \"Trieste\"]], [[90th Light Infantry Division (Wehrmacht)|90th Light Division]], [[80th Infantry Division La Spezia (Airlanding)|80th Infantry Division \"La Spezia\"]], [[16th Motorised Division Pistoia|16th Motorised Division \"Pistoia\"]], [[164th Infantry Division (Wehrmacht)|164th Light ''Afrika'' Division]] and the [[15th Panzer Division (Wehrmacht)|15th Panzer Division]] with 32 operational tanks. In reserve were the [[21st Panzer Division (Wehrmacht)|21st Panzer Division]] and the [[10th Panzer Division (Wehrmacht)|10th Panzer Division]] with 110 operational tanks. The line from Djebel Tebaga\u2013Djebel Melab was held by the {{lang|it|Raggruppamento Sahariano}}.{{sfn|Playfair|2004|p=333}} The British survey of the Mareth Line, the positions of [[Zarat, Tunisia|Zarat]] sudest (Zaret South-West), Ouerzi, Ouerzi Ouest (Ouerzi West), Ouerzi Est (Ouerzi East), Ksiba Ouest and Ksiba Est being of particular interest, was assisted by General Marcel Rime-Bruneau, a former Chief of Staff of the Tunisian garrison and Captain Paul Mezan, the former Garrison Engineer of the Mareth Line.{{sfn|Playfair|2004|p=332}}\n\n===Battle of the Mareth Line===\n{{Main article|Battle of the Mareth Line}}\n\n[[File:Mareth line object.jpg|thumb|{{center|Infantry bunker of the Mareth Line}}]]\nOn 19 March 1943, the Eighth Army made a frontal assault against the Mareth Line in Operation Pugilist. The [[50th (Northumbrian) Infantry Division|50th Northumbrian Infantry Division]] penetrated the Line near [[Zarat, Tunisia|Zarat]] but was driven back by the [[33rd Infantry Division (Wehrmacht)|15th Panzer Division]] and the{{lang|it|Giovani Fascisti}} on 22 March.<ref>[https://adviceandresearch.blogspot.com/2019/06/division-giovani-fascisti-in-1943.html Giovani Fascisti division at Mareth]</ref> Earlier reconnaissance by the [[Long Range Desert Group]] had shown that the Line could be outflanked. A force could pass through the southern Matmata Hills, reach the Tebaga Gap from the west and pass on to the coastal plain behind the Mareth Line. At the same time as Pugilist, Montgomery had sent the [[2nd New Zealand Division]] around the Matmata Hills but its attack was contained at the Tebaga Gap from 21 to 24 March. Montgomery sent the [[1st (United Kingdom) Division|1st Armoured Division]] ([[X Corps (United Kingdom)|X Corps]]) to reinforce the attack at the Tebaga Gap. The British attacked again in [[Battle of the Mareth Line#Operation Supercharge II|Operation Supercharge II]] on 26 March and broke through the gap the next day. This success, combined with a fresh frontal assault, made the Mareth Line untenable but the Italian 1st Army escaped encirclement when the 1st Armoured Division was held up at El Hamma and the Axis forces retreated to [[Wadi Akarit]], {{convert|60|km|mi|order=flip}} to the north.\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{reflist|20em}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |title=The Oxford Companion to World War II |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford |year=2001 |editor-first=I. C. B. |editor-last=Dear |isbn=0-19-860446-7}}\n* {{cite book |ref={{harvid|Ford|2012}}\n|last=Ford |first=K. |others=Steve Noon |title=The Mareth Line 1943: The End in Africa |year=2012 |publisher=Osprey |location=Oxford |edition=ebook |isbn=978-1-78096-094-4}}\n* {{cite book |last=Jackson |first=P. |title=France and the Nazi Menace: Intelligence and Policy Making, 1933\u20131939 |year=2000 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford |isbn=0-19820-834-0 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |ref={{harvid|Kaufmann|Kaufmann|2006}}\n|last1=Kaufmann |first1=J. E. |last2=Kaufmann |first2=H. W. |title=Fortress France: The Maginot Line and French Defenses in World War II |year=2006 |publisher=Praeger Security International (Greenwood Publishing) |location=Westport, CT |edition=online scan |isbn=0-275-98345-5}}\n* {{cite book |ref={{harvid|Playfair|1954}}\n|first1= I. S. O. |last1=Playfair |author1-link=Ian Stanley Ord Playfair |first2=G. M. S. |last2=Stitt |first3= C. J. C. |last3=Molony |first4= S. E. |last4=Toomer |editor-last=Butler |editor-first=J. R. M. |editor-link=James Ramsay Montagu Butler |series=History of the Second World War, United Kingdom Military Series |title=The Mediterranean and Middle East: The Early Successes Against Italy (to May 1941) |volume=I |publisher=[[HMSO]] |edition=4th impr.|year=1954 |isbn=1-84574-065-3 |display-authors=1}}\n* {{cite book |ref={{harvid|Playfair|2004}}\n|first1= I. S. O. |last1=Playfair |first2= C. J. C. |last2=and Molony |first3= F. C. |last3=Flynn |first4= T. P. |last4=Gleave |editor-last=Butler |editor-first=J. R. M. |title=The Mediterranean and Middle East: The Destruction of the Axis Forces in Africa |volume=IV |series=History of the Second World War United Kingdom Military Series |orig-year=1966 |year=2004 |publisher=HMSO |location=London |edition=pbk. facs repr. Naval & Military Press, Uckfield |isbn=1-84574-068-8 |display-authors=1}}\n* {{cite book |last=Prior-Palmer |first=Brigadier G. E. |url=http://www.warlinks.com/armour/8th_armoured/chapter_2.html |accessdate=3 June 2015 |title=A Short History of the 8th Armoured Brigade |chapter=II, Medenine to Tunis |date=March 1946 |publisher=H.Q. 8th Armoured Brigade |location=Hanover |others=no isbn}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book |last=Gauch\u00e9 |first=Maurice |series=Archives d'histoire contemporaine |title=Le Deuxi\u00e8me Bureau au Travail, 1935\u20131940 |trans-title=The [[Deuxi\u00e8me Bureau]] at Work |language=French |year=1953 |publisher=Amiot Dumont |location=Paris |oclc=3093195}}\n* {{cite book |last=Stevens |first=Major-General W. G. |series=The Official History of New Zealand in the Second World War 1939\u20131945 |title=Bardia to Enfidaville |chapter=8\u201310 |url=http://www.nzetc.org/tm/scholarly/tei-WH2Bard-c8-1.html |location=Wellington, NZ |publisher=Historical Publications Branch |year=1962 |oclc=4377202}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Mareth Line}}\n* [http://cgsc.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/singleitem/collection/p4013coll8/id/4161/rec/1 Strader, J. W. Tactical Bomber Operations in the ETO (1944)]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110710212242/http://www.exploguide.com/site/mareth-line-military-museum-mareth Travel tips to visit the Mareth Line museum]\n\n{{World War II}}\n\n[[Category:Tunisian Campaign]]\n[[Category:World War II defensive lines]]\n[[Category:World War II sites in Tunisia]]\n", "name_user": "Keith-264", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDemilitarisation and Axis occupation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mareth_Line"}
{"title_page": "Diodato", "text_new": "{{expand language|topic=|langcode=IT|otherarticle=Diodato (cantante)|date=March 2015}}\n{{short description|Italian singer and songwriter}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| background       = solo_singer\n| name             = Diodato\n| image            = Rocking with Antonio Diodato (cropped).jpg\n| caption          = Diodato in 2016\n| birth_place      = [[Aosta]], [[Italy]]\n| birth_name       = Antonio Diodato\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1981|08|30}}\n| genre            = [[Pop rock]]\n| years_active     = 2007\u2013present\n| occupation       = Singer, songwriter\n}}\n\n'''Antonio Diodato''' (born 30 August 1981), known simply as '''Diodato''', is an Italian singer-songwriter, he is known among italians as \"Mimmo\", this nickname was given to him by another italian celebrity, Brigantony.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.diodatomusic.it/|title=diodatomusic.it &#124; Sito ufficiale di Diodato}}</ref> He won the [[Sanremo Music Festival 2020|70th edition]] of the [[Sanremo Music Festival]] with the song \"[[Fai rumore]]\" and was scheduled to represent [[Italy in the Eurovision Song Contest 2020|Italy]] in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2020]] held in [[Rotterdam]], the [[Netherlands]]. Unfortunately, his performance will be postponed due to COVID-19 concerns.\n\n==Career==\nHe has released two studio albums, ''E forse sono pazzo'' (LeNarcisse/Goodfellas)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rockol.it/recensioni-musicali/album/5600/diodato-e-forse-sono-pazzo|title=\u221a Recensioni &#124; Dischi &#124; Diodato - E Forse Sono Pazzo su Rockol|first=Rockol com|last=s.r.l|website=Rockol}}</ref> and ''A ritrovar bellezza'' (LeNarcisse/[[RCA]]/SonyMusic).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radioitalia.it/news/diodato/nuova_uscita/9169_a_ritrovar_bellezza_le_canzoni_degli_anni_sessanta_secondo_diodato.php|title=A Ritrovar Bellezza, le canzoni degli anni Sessanta secondo Diodato|website=Radio Italia}}</ref> In 2014 he participated in the [[Sanremo Music Festival]] and won the [[MTV Italian Music Awards]] for Best New Generation, The Deezer Band Of The Year Award and the Fabrizio de Andr\u00e9 Award.<ref>Big Time http://www.bigtimeweb.it/diodato</ref> He won the [[Sanremo Music Festival 2020]] with the song \"[[Fai rumore]]\" and will also represent [[Italy in the Eurovision Song Contest 2020|Italy]] at the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2020]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Sanremo 2020: Ecco chi sono i 22 Big in gara della 70esima edizione del Festival|url=https://www.comingsoon.it/tv/anticipazioni/sanremo-2020-ecco-chi-sono-i-22-big-in-gara-della-70esima-edizione-del/n98831/|website=Coming Soon|date=31 December 2019|access-date=5 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Italy: Diodato wins Sanremo 2020!|url=https://eurovision.tv/story/italian-national-selection-sanremo-2020|website=Eurovision.tv|date=9 February 2020|access-date=9 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n===Albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:12em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:15em;\"| Details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"1\"| Peak chart positions\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Federazione Industria Musicale Italiana|ITA]]<br/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://italiancharts.com/search.asp?search=Diodato&cat=a|title=Discographie Diodato (Albums)|website=italiancharts.com|accessdate=20 February 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''E forse sono pazzo''\n|\n* Released: April 2013\n* Format: Digital download\n* Label: Le Narcisse\n| \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''A ritrovar bellezza''\n|\n* Released: 29 October 2014\n* Format: Digital download\n* Label: Le Narcisse\n| \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Cosa siamo diventati''\n|\n* Released: 27 January 2017\n* Format: Digital download\n* Label: Carosello Records\n| 48\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Che vita meravigliosa]]''\n|\n* Released: 14 February 2020\n* Forma